<knowl mode="exercise" xmlns="https://spatext.clontz.org" version="0.2">
    
    <knowl>
        <intro>
            <p>Consider the function <m>f(x,y)=\frac{ {{connum}} }{ {{conden}} }</m>.</p>
        </intro>
        
        
        <knowl>
            <content>
                <p>
                    Find the limit <m>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\to ({{x0}},{{y0}})} \frac{ {{connum}} }{ {{conden}} }</m>.
                    
                    
                </p>
            </content>
            <outtro>
                <p>
                   <m>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\to ({{x0}},{{y0}})} \frac{ {{connum}} }{ {{conden}} }={{conlim}}</m>.
                </p>
             </outtro>
         </knowl>
        
        
        
    </knowl>
    
    
    <knowl>
        <intro>
            <p>Consider the function <m>g(x,y)=\frac{ {{divnum}} }{ {{divden}} }</m>.</p>
        </intro>
        
        
        <knowl>
            <content>
                <p>
                    Find the limit <m>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\to ({{x0}},{{y0}})} \frac{ {{divnum}} }{ {{divden}} }</m>  along the <m>x</m>-axis.
                    
                    
                </p>
            </content>
            <outtro>
                <p>
                   <m>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\to ({{x0}},{{y0}})} \frac{ {{divnum}} }{ {{divden}} }</m> along the <m>x</m>-axis is <m>{{limx}}</m>.
                </p>
             </outtro>
         </knowl>
        
        <knowl>
            <content>
                <p>
                    Find the limit <m>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\to ({{x0}},{{y0}})} \frac{ {{divnum}} }{ {{divden}} }</m>  along the <m>y</m>-axis.
                    
                    
                </p>
            </content>
            <outtro>
                <p>
                   <m>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\to ({{x0}},{{y0}})} \frac{ {{divnum}} }{ {{divden}} }</m> along the <m>y</m>-axis is <m>{{limy}}</m>.
                </p>
             </outtro>
         </knowl>
        
        <knowl>
            <content>
                <p>
                    Find the limit <m>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\to ({{x0}},{{y0}})} \frac{ {{divnum}} }{ {{divden}} }</m>  along the <m>y=x</m> line.
                    
                    
                </p>
            </content>
            <outtro>
                <p>
                   <m>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\to ({{x0}},{{y0}})} \frac{ {{divnum}} }{ {{divden}} }</m> along the <m>y=x</m> line is <m>{{limt}}</m>.
                </p>
             </outtro>
         </knowl>
        
        <knowl>
            <content>
                <p>
                    Explain why the limit <m>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\to ({{x0}},{{y0}})} \frac{ {{divnum}} }{ {{divden}} }</m>  is undefined.
                    
                    
                </p>
            </content>
            <outtro>
                <p>
                   There are at least two trajectories to <m>(0,0)</m> for which the resulting limits do not agree.</p>
                
                <p>    
                    For example: <m>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\to ({{x0}},{{y0}}), y=0} \frac{ {{divnum}} }{ {{divden}} }
                    ={{limx}}\neq{{limy}}=\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\to ({{x0}},{{y0}}), x=0}\frac{ {{divnum}} }{ {{divden}} }.</m>
                </p>
             </outtro>
         </knowl>
        
        
        
    </knowl>
    
    
    
        
                    
                    
             
